pan><hr size=1> There are so many people who play wizards who won't ever realize the intricacies of their class. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :( --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/frown.gif ALT=":("><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=konekokrystalpaw>Koneko Krystalpaw</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Visitor</span><br>  Posts: 3<br> <font color=#ffffff>(4/15/03 9:34:39 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub140.ezboard.com/fgraffeswizardcompilationfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=25965.topic&index=28>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.kindredintellect.com/images/cat3d.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: ...</span><hr size=1> As long as you were in melee range (so minimum ping pong happened) I don't see anything wrong with this alternative tactic. I've had similar success rotating stuns with a pally friend of mine, while my husbands ranger sits back and fires at the unrooted but stationary mob. In this case, i concussion liberally between stuns to make sure the pally keeps the aggro. It's not alway the most efficient tactic, but its an option. In fact I would guess it left your monk healthy and ready to pull as soon as the fights were over. Alot of clerics are very used to a &quot;role&quot; just as alot of wizards are. Your cleric may have had a hard time attention wise keeping up with 2 targets that likely didn't have more than 2k hp. Alternative tactics require that the majority of the group is able to adapt. It seems to me like the cleric was just frustrated with a change from the norm, and wanted to go back to a traditional tactic. Sounds like you were more than able to drop aggro when asked, so the clerics nasty comments about how to play your class seem unwarranted to me. I think the key to playing a good wizard is getting aggro only when you want to get it. I would bet there are dozens of different tactics for achieving that in varying situations tho. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=targonis>Targonis</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Sorcerer</span><br>  Posts: 765<br> <font color=#ffffff>(4/15/03 9:40:00 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub140.ezboard.com/fgraffeswizardcompilationfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=25965.topic&index=29>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: ...</span><hr size=1> Mysthawk, the logic is fairly simple(to me at least).  My thinking on this is that the power of wizards is that we can do the most damage in the shortest period of time.  Also, dead mobs don't do damage, so the quicker you kill a mob, the less damage the tanks take, which means the cleric(s) don't need to heal as much.<br>
  Now, if you ride the agro line perfectly, you will get summoned, but the mob will turn back to the tanks before even attacking you.  So, you are doing the max DPS without taking any cleric mana.  If you have your epic, and have HP buffs, even if you agro a mob that breaks through your epic rune, you won't need healing until after the mob is dead, and even then it won't be a HUGE level of healing.  You've saved cleric mana by killing faster.<br>
<br>
This of course, implies that you can stay alive, and can ride close to the agro line without making the cleric heal you continually.  It also implies that you have the hit points to take a few hits without getting killed.  One thing many people never understood is why STAMINA is listed as a primary stat for wizards.  Take a look at character creation, you will see that Intelligence AND Stamina are the primary stats.  We get self-only runes through our advancement because we WILL occasionally get agro.<br>
<br>
Then, there is also the mindset of many wizards that has developed over time because wizards were relegated to taxi service by MANY guilds and people during the Kunark and Velious days(pre-AA abilities).  The damage output from melees compared to casters JUMPED up with Kunark's release.  It got to the point where people wouldn't notice that a wizard was in the group unless an evac was needed.  The solution that some of us came up with was to make our presence FELT in groups.  Perhaps not on EVERY mob, but at least here and there, we'd nuke a LOT, the mob would drop quick, and the people in the group would notice.  Then we'd med up for a few more mobs, then do it again.  Wizards who only nuked once or twice per mob to avoid going OOM just wern't noticed by most groups, so were considered expendable.<br>
<br>
I'm happy to see that those days are generally gone, spell crits can be seen, the melees see and feel it when we are in the group, but the old, &quot;tank/cleric/enchanter&quot; core is still present.  As the player base learns how to tell the difference between a GOOD wizard and one that sucks, getting groups has become less difficult.  Many still don't know the difference between a wizard that hasn't hit Master yet and one that's hit Sage, but they are slowly learning.  The NEED to ride the agro line has gone down as we can pump out good damage without needing to push as hard as well.  Many still do it, but it's also a function of style at that point.<br>
 <p>Targonis Manastorm<br>
Level 65 Wizard<br>
The Nameless Server<br>
